\begin_layout Subsection
Dominance
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The following definitions introduce the concept of a strictly dominant strategy
 equilibrium.
 In a strictly dominant strategy equilibrium, players play their strategy
 irrespective of the action of others.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\emph on
Definition:
\emph default
 Strategy 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}\in S_{i}$
\end_inset

 strictly dominates strategy 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}^{\prime}\neq s_{i}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

 for player 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}(s_{i},s_{-i})>u_{i}(s_{i}^{\prime},s_{-i})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{-i}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{-i}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 strictly dominates another strategies 
\begin_inset Formula $s'_{i}$
\end_inset

, then that strategy is strictly dominated and can be eliminated from considerat
ion by 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\emph on
Definition:
\emph default
 Strategy 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}^{\prime}$
\end_inset

 is strictly dominated if there is an 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}\in S_{i}$
\end_inset

 that strictly dominates it.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 strictly dominates all other strategies, then it is strictly dominant.
 Note that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}$
\end_inset

 is by definition unique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\emph on
Definition:
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}\in S_{i}$
\end_inset

 is strictly dominant for 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 if it strictly dominates all 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}^{\prime}\neq s_{i}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An equilibrium in strictly dominant strategies exists if all players have
 a strictly dominant strategy.
 Note that from the above, a strictly dominant strategy is necessarily unique.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\emph on
Definition:
\emph default
 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{\ast}\in S$
\end_inset

 is a strictly dominant strategy equilibrium if 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}(s_{i}^{\ast},s_{-i})>u_{i}(s_{i},s_{-i})$
\end_inset

 for all players 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in N$
\end_inset

 and for all strategy profiles 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{-i}\in S_{-i},$
\end_inset

 that is, if all elements of 
\begin_inset Formula $s^{\ast}$
\end_inset

 are strictly dominant strategies.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\emph on
Example:
\emph default
 The strictly dominant strategy equilibrium in the Prisoners' Dilemma is
 {D,D}.
 Indeed, D is a strictly dominant strategy for player 1 as 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}(D,C)>u_{1}(C,C)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{1}(D,D)>u_{1}(C,D)$
\end_inset

.
 The same holds for player 
\begin_inset Formula $2.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\emph on
Remark:
\emph default
 One can also define weak dominance as follows: Strategy 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}\in S_{i}$
\end_inset

 weakly dominates (or simply 
\begin_inset Quotes grd
\end_inset

dominates
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) strategy 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{i}^{\prime}\neq s_{i}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{i}$
\end_inset

 for player 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}(s_{i},s_{-i})\geq u_{i}(s_{i}^{\prime},s_{-i})$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{-i}$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{-i}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

