\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\end_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
As in the above, the usual way to find equilibria of an extensive form game
 is to reduce it to a normal form game and find the NE of that normal form
 game.
 The equilibria of the extensive form game will be a subset of the NE of
 the normal form game, as the normal form game neglects important information
 about the succesion of actions in the game.
 We see below how the set of Nash equilibria can be parsed down through
 a process of 
\emph on
backward induction
\emph default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Backward induction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
From the above, the entrant stays out because she expects the incumbent
 to fight upon entry with probability at least half.
 However, since the entrant stays out, this is a completely arbitrary belief
 as there is no way for the entrant to verify that prediction.
 Is that arbitrary belief reasonable? When the entrant enters, then the
 incumbent will always find it best to accomodate.
 Therefore, the only credible belief for the entrant is that when the entrant
 enters, then the incumbent would accomodate.
 Therefore, it is not reasonable for the incumbent to believe that the incumbent
 would fight with any positive probability if she were to enter, because
 it is not credible for the incumbent to actually fight upon entry.
 One can thus state that the only credible equilibria of the game are those
 that survive a process of backward induction where, beginning from the
 last stage, actions that players will not choose in that stage are eliminated
 from consideration.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For example, in the game of entry deterrence, the incumbent will not fight
 when called upon to choose its action.
 Eliminating 
\begin_inset Quotes els
\end_inset

fight upon entry
\begin_inset Quotes ers
\end_inset

 from consideration, the game that remains is thus a choice for the entrant
 between staying out, which gives payoff 
\begin_inset Formula $0,$
\end_inset

 and entering, which, by backward induction, will give a payoff of 
\begin_inset Formula $1.$
\end_inset

 The entrant thus chooses to enter.
 The only equilibrium that survives this process of backward induction is
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \text{Enter, Accomodate}\right\} .$
\end_inset


\end_layout

