\begin_layout Description
Definition: A Bayesian game of incomplete information consists of 
\end_layout

\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Enumerate
Players, labelled 
\begin_inset Formula $i\in N=\left\{ 1,...,n\right\} $
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Types, for each player 
\begin_inset Formula $i,$
\end_inset

 there is a set 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{i}$
\end_inset

 of possibles types, labeled 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}.$
\end_inset

 Player 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 might be of different types that have different payoffs, but all possible
 types of player 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 play the same role in the game.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Actions, for each player 
\begin_inset Formula $i,$
\end_inset

 there is a set 
\begin_inset Formula $A_{i}$
\end_inset

 of possible actions, labeled 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{i}.$
\end_inset

 This means that whatever 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

's type, he has access to the same range of action.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Beliefs, for each pair 
\begin_inset Formula $(i,t_{i}),$
\end_inset

 a probability distribution over 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{-i},$
\end_inset

 written 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{i}(t_{-i}|t_{i}).$
\end_inset

This denotes what player 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

of type 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{i}$
\end_inset

 believes the type of other player are.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Payoffs, for each player 
\begin_inset Formula $i,$
\end_inset

 a vNM utility function 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}:A\times T\rightarrow\mathbb{R}.$
\end_inset

 As said above, payoffs depend not only on the identity of the player, but
 on his type.
 
\end_layout

