\begin_layout Subsubsection
Auctions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Auctions are a specific example of Bayesian games, whereby one or many buyers
 and one or many sellers must reach an agreement over the exchange of one
 or many goods.
 This agreement may be about exchange price, quantity exchanged, and the
 identity and allocation to sellers and buyers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We will examine two very simple mechanisms: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
One is such that a seller must decide to which of two buyers to sell one
 indivisible good in its possession, and at what price.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The other is such that one buyer is faced with one seller with one indivisible
 good, and must reach an agreement over the price at which that one indivisible
 good will be exchanged.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
There are a variety of auction mechanisms which could be applied to either
 of the two situations, and there are also a variety of other situations
 where auction mechanisms could be applied.
 We will examine only the first price sealed bid auction as applied to the
 first situation, and the double auction as applied to the second situation.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\emph on
1) First Price Sealed Bid Auction
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Two buyers, 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j,$
\end_inset

 submit sealed bids to a seller.
 The highest bidder wins the object, and pays his/her bid to the seller.
 The object is worth 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 to buyer 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{j}$
\end_inset

 to buyer 
\begin_inset Formula $j.$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 knows 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 but not 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{j},$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 knows 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{j}$
\end_inset

 but not 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}.$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 believes 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{j}$
\end_inset

 is distributed uniformly over 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1],$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 believes 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 is distributed uniformly over 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1].$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Strategies are of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}:[0,1]\rightarrow\mathbb{R},$
\end_inset

 which for any 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{i}$
\end_inset

 assigns a bid 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}(v_{i}).$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Payoffs can be represented as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula $u_{i}(b_{i};v_{i})=\begin{cases}
\begin{tabular}{c}
 \ensuremath{0\text{ if }b_{i}<b_{j}}\\
\ensuremath{\frac{v_{i}-b_{i}}{2}\text{ if }b_{i}=b_{j}}\\
\ensuremath{v_{i}-b_{i}\text{ if }b_{i}>b_{j}}
\end{tabular}\end{cases}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We are going to looks for a linear bidding strategy, s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}(v_{i})=\alpha+\beta v_{i}.$
\end_inset

 Neglecting the case where 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}=b_{j}$
\end_inset

 (an event of probability measure 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

), and assuming 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}\in\lbrack\alpha,\alpha+\beta],$
\end_inset

 the expected payoff to player 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 who is bidding 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}$
\end_inset

 is then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
E(u_{j}(b_{j};v_{j})) & =\Pr(b_{j}\geq\alpha+\beta v_{i})(v_{j}-b_{j})\\
 & =\Pr(\frac{b_{j}-\alpha}{\beta}\geq v_{i})(v_{j}-b_{j})\\
 & =\frac{b_{j}-\alpha}{\beta}(v_{j}-b_{j})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 This is a concave function which attains a maximum for 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}=\frac{v_{j}+\alpha}{2}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 indeed chooses 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{j}=\frac{v_{j}+\alpha}{2}.$
\end_inset

 Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
E(u_{i}(b_{i};v_{i})) & =\Pr(b_{i}\geq\frac{v_{j}+\alpha}{2})(v_{i}-b_{i})\\
 & =\Pr(2b_{i}-\alpha\geq v_{j})(v_{i}-b_{i})\\
 & =(2b_{i}-\alpha)(v_{i}-b_{i})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 This is a concave function that attains its maximum for 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}=\frac{\alpha+2v_{i}}{4}.$
\end_inset

 Combining the two equations for 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{i}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{\text{j}}$
\end_inset

, one obtains 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\frac{1}{2}.$
\end_inset

 Each bidder thus bids half his/her own valuation for the good.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\emph on
Remark:
\emph default
 This linear bidding strategy is the unique symmetric Bayesian equilibrium
 if valuations are uniformly distributed.
 There may be other, non-symmetric Bayesian strategies, and if valuations
 are not uniformly distributed, then the linear bidding strategy is not
 necessarily optimal.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description

\emph on
Exercise:
\emph default
 Consider the three following alternative bidding rules, and solve for the
 optimal bidding strategy: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The second price auction, whereby the highest bidder wins the good and pays
 the bid of the second highest bidder.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The `all pay' auction, whereby the highest bidder wins the good and both
 bidders pay their own bid.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The `loser pays' auction, whereby the highest bidder wins the good and the
 second highest bidder pays the bid of the highest bidder.
 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph

\emph on
2) Double Auction
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A buyer with valuation 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{b}\sim U[0,1]$
\end_inset

 for a good is faced with a seller with valuation 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{s}\sim U[0,1]$
\end_inset

 for a good.
 Both have to submit their bids (offered price for the buyer, asked price
 for the seller), simultaneously.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{b}<p_{s}$
\end_inset

 then there is no trade.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{b}\geq p_{s},$
\end_inset

 then they split the difference, so the trade price is 
\begin_inset Formula $p=\frac{p_{s}+p_{b}}{2}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Payoffs are thus as follows:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula $u_{b}(p_{b};v_{b})=\begin{cases}
\begin{tabular}{c}
 \ensuremath{0\text{ if }p_{b}<p_{s}}\\
\ensuremath{v_{b}-\frac{p_{s}+p_{b}}{2}\text{ if }p_{b}\geq p_{s}}
\end{tabular}\end{cases}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\align center
\begin_inset Formula $u_{s}(p_{s};v_{s})=\begin{cases}
\begin{tabular}{c}
 \ensuremath{0\text{ if }p_{b}<p_{s}}\\
\ensuremath{\frac{p_{s}+p_{b}}{2}-v_{s}\text{ if }p_{b}\geq p_{s}}
\end{tabular}\end{cases}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As before, one will consider linear bidding strategies s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{b}(v_{b})=\alpha+\beta v_{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{s}(v_{s})=\gamma+\delta v_{s}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the strategy of the buyer.
 The expected payoff to the buyer who is offering 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{b}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E(u_{b}(p_{b};v_{b}))=\Pr(p_{b}\geq p_{s})(v_{b}-\frac{E(p_{s}\mid p_{b}\geq p_{s})+p_{b}}{2})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
with
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
E(p_{s}\text{ }|\text{ }p_{b} & \geq p_{s})=E(\gamma+\delta v_{s}\mid p_{b}\geq\gamma+\delta v_{s})\\
 & =\gamma+\delta E(v_{s}\mid\frac{p_{b}-\gamma}{\delta}\geq v_{s})\\
 & =\gamma+\delta\frac{p_{b}-\gamma}{2\delta}\\
 & =\frac{1}{2}\gamma+\frac{1}{2}p_{b}
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 so
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
E(u_{b}(p_{b};v_{b})) & =\Pr(\frac{p_{s}-\gamma}{\delta}\geq v_{s})(v_{b}-\frac{\frac{1}{2}\gamma+\frac{1}{2}p_{b}+p_{b}}{2})\\
 & =\frac{p_{b}-\gamma}{\delta}(v_{b}-\frac{\gamma+3p_{b}}{4})
\end{align*}

\end_inset

 This is a concave function that is maximized for 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{b}=\frac{\gamma+2v_{b}}{3}.$
\end_inset

 Similarly, the optimal bidding strategy for the seller is to ask 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{s}=\frac{\alpha+\beta+2v_{s}}{3}.$
\end_inset

 Combining the two equations for 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{b}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{s}$
\end_inset

 with the assumed expression of their value, one obtains 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta=\delta=\frac{2}{3}.$
\end_inset

 while 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\frac{\gamma}{3}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\frac{\alpha+\beta}{3}.$
\end_inset

 This is solved for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=\frac{1}{4}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\frac{1}{12}.$
\end_inset

 This means that both buyer and seller will 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

shade
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 their valuation by a factor of 2/3 and there is a range of values of 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{s}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $v_{b}$
\end_inset

 for which no trade ever takes place.
\end_layout

