\begin_deeper
\begin_layout Standard
The `how' is rather complicated, and involves assuming that players have
 access to publicly observable randomizing devices so that for example,
 they know when to play 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and when to play 
\begin_inset Formula $D$
\end_inset

.
 This public randomizing device would draw their strategy at random according
 to pre-determined probabilities.
 It would be possible for either player to check the other player played
 what they were supposed to play.
 We can prove that the greatest payoff that may be achieved subject to a
 given 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta$
\end_inset

 is such that both players play symmetric strategies, i.e.
 both play C with the same probability.
 The probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 with which both 1 and 2 are asked to play C determines their payoff 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
 Indeed, I will have 
\begin_inset Formula $a=5p^{2}+7p(1-p)+(1-p)^{2}.$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1 will not deviate from playing C when told to do so s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $5p+\delta\frac{a}{1-\delta}\geq7p+1(1-p)+\frac{\delta}{1-\delta}$
\end_inset

 (the constraint for 2 is the same).
 I can thus conclude, replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 by its expression in 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and rewriting the above equation, that I will need that 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be set such that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{a-1}{1+p}\geq\frac{1-\delta}{\delta}$
\end_inset

.
 Note that, as stated previously, for any 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta\geq\frac{1}{3}$
\end_inset

 then 
\begin_inset Formula $p=1$
\end_inset

 and full cooperation can be sustained.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta=\frac{1}{4}$
\end_inset

, no cooperation is sustainable (
\begin_inset Formula $p=0)$
\end_inset

.
